ht: 25.6806px; line-height: 1.6;"><br></p><h2>What Are Lumens and Watts and=
 What is the Difference between Them=EF=BC=9F</h2><p style=3D"text-align: j=
ustify;">When selecting lighting solutions, it's common practice to referen=
ce wattage. Traditionally, wattage has been associated with a bulb's output=
, with the assumption that higher wattage correlates to increased brightnes=
s. However, wattage fundamentally indicates electrical power consumption. F=
or instance, a 60-watt incandescent bulb consumes 60 watts per hour. It's c=
rucial to understand that wattage does not directly quantify light output.&=
nbsp;</p><p style=3D"text-align: justify;"><br></p><p style=3D"text-align: =
justify;">In contemporary lighting, lumens serve as the definitive metric f=
or brightness. Lumens directly measure the total amount of visible light em=
itted by a source, representing the perceived brightness. A higher lumen va=
lue signifies greater light output. To illustrate, an 800-lumen LED bulb de=
livers a light output equivalent to a traditional 60-watt incandescent bulb=
.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"text-align: justify;"><br>Therefore, for modern ligh=
ting procurement, lumens should be the primary consideration for assessing =
brightness, while wattage should be used to determine energy consumption. I=
n essence, lumens define brightness, and watts define power consumption.&nb=
sp;</p><p style=3D"text-align: justify;"><br>The shift to lumens reflects a=
dvancements in energy-efficient lighting technologies. Lumen provides a mor=
e accurate representation of a bulb's brightness. Different bulb types may =
produce the same lumens with varying wattages.=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8B</=
p><br>=E2=80=8B<br><div style=3D"text-align: center;"><img src=3D"https://w=
