LED bulbs:</strong> 80=E2=80=93150+ lm/W<br><br></p></li></ul><p style=3D"t=
ext-align: justify;">Higher efficacy means more light output per watt, indi=
cating better energy efficiency. In addition, Most LED bulbs, fluorescent l=
amps, or other lighting products list their luminous efficacy on the packag=
ing or datasheet. Or, you can calculate it yourself if you know the luminou=
s flux and power consumption. Here is the equation:&nbsp;<br><br></p><p sty=
le=3D"text-align: center;"><strong><em>=E2=80=8BWatt =3D Lumens =C3=B7 Lumi=
nous Efficiency&nbsp;</em><br>=E2=80=8B<br></strong></p><p style=3D"text-al=
ign: justify;">Wondering how 800 lumens to watts works? For example, if you=
 need 800 lumens of brightness, and the LED light you choose has an efficie=
ncy of 100 lumens per watt, it only needs about 8 watts of power. The same =
trick works for other common cases. 500 lumens to watts is 5W, and 1000 lum=
ens to watts is 10W. This method can help you choose a bulb that is both br=
ight and energy efficient.<br></p></span></div><h2>Choose a Bulb Based on t=
